		Rule
		(or, really, Axiom CIP).

Let's check: given \uvec{u},\uvec{v} in \R^n, we have


		\utrans{\uvec{v}} A \uvec{u}
		\amp = \utrans{(v_1 \uvec{e}_1 + \dotsb + v_n \uvec{e}_n)} A (u_1 \uvec{e}_1 + \dotsb + u_n \uvec{e}_n)

		\amp = (v_1 \utrans{\uvec{e}}_1 + \dotsb + v_n \utrans{\uvec{e}}_n) (u_1 A \uvec{e}_1 + \dotsb + u_n A \uvec{e}_n)

		\amp = \sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^n v_j u_i \utrans{\uvec{e}}_j A \uvec{e}_i

		\amp = \sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^n u_i v_j \inprod{\uvec{e}_i}{\uvec{e}_j}

		\amp = \inprod{u_1 \uvec{e}_1 + \dotsb + u_n \uvec{e}_n}{v_1 \uvec{e}_1 + \dotsb + v_n \uvec{e}_n}

		\amp = \uvecinprod{u}{v}

,
as desired.

It is straightfoward to verify that A = \utrans{P} P is symmetric by showing \utrans{A} = A. So we will focus on the positive part of the definition of . Suppose \uvec{x} is a nonzero column vector in \R^n. Then,
\utrans{\uvec{x}} A \uvec{x} \amp = \utrans{\uvec{x}} \utrans{P} P \uvec{x} \amp = \utrans{(P \uvec{x})} (P \uvec{x}) \amp = \dotprod{(P \uvec{x})}{(P \uvec{x})} \amp = 
orm{P \uvec{x}}^2 . We assumed both P invertible and \uvec{x} 
eq \zerovec, so P \uvec{x} 
eq \zerovec must be true as well (). Which also means 
orm{P \uvec{x}} 
eq 0 (Rule of ). And therefore \utrans{\uvec{x}} A \uvec{x} = 
orm{P \uvec{x}}^2 > 0 , as desired.
